{
  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "Figure 6a shows the distribution histogram of the R EXT Hα values for the stellar sources in the MRS time-domain sample of solar-like stars employed in this work, and Figure 6b shows the distribution of R EXT Hα with N obs.",
    "In Figure 6, the histogram and data points in light gray are for the full sample, and the overlapping histogram and data points in blue are for the sample of R EXT Hα > 3 × δR EXT Hα (i.e., the sample with signals above the three-times-uncertainty threshold).",
    "It can be seen from Figure 6a that the peak of the R EXT Hα distribution is at about 10 -6, which is one order of magnitude smaller than the values of R Hα (about 10 -5; see Section 4.1).",
    "It can also be seen from Figure 6a that a considerable proportion of the stellar sources in our sample have the R EXT Hα values below the 3×δR EXT Hα threshold (the median of 3×δR EXT Hα being about 6.2×10 -7), and Figure 6b further indicates that this portion of the sample is generally associated with smaller N obs.",
    "As N obs increases, the random fluctuations between the multiple measurements bring the lower envelope of the R EXT Hα values approach the threshold, as demonstrated in Figure 6b."
  ],
